04157nam a22005655i 9780231538244DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20142014nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2014009808  a(OCoLC)984546142  a97802315382447 a10.7312/robe168182doi  a(DE-B1597)458481  a(OCoLC)892244504  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aTR183b.R6324 2014 7aPHI0010002bisacsh04a770.11 aRoberts, John, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPhotography and Its Violations /cJohn Roberts.  aPilot project. eBook available to selected US libraries only 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (232 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aColumbia Themes in Philosophy, Social Criticism, and the Arts00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Social Ontology of Photography -- tPart I. The Document, the Figural, and the Index -- t1. Photography and Its Truth-Event -- t2. The Political Form of Photography Today -- t3. “Fragment, Experiment, Dissonant Prologue”: Modernism, Realism, and the Photodocument -- t4. Two Models of Labor: Figurality and Nonfigurality in Recent Photography -- tPart II. Abstraction, Violation, and Empathy -- t5. Photography After the Photograph: Event, Archive, and the Nonsymbolic -- t6. Photography, Abstraction, and the Social Production of Space -- t7. Violence, Photography, and the Inhuman -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTheorists critique photography for "objectifying" its subjects and manipulating appearances for the sake of art. In this bold counterargument, John Roberts recasts photography's violating powers of disclosure and aesthetic technique as part of a complex "social ontology" that exposes the hierarchies, divisions, and exclusions behind appearances.The photographer must "arrive unannounced" and "get in the way of the world," Roberts argues, committing photography to the truth-claims of the spectator over the self-interests and sensitivities of the subject. Yet even though the violating capacity of the photograph results from external power relations, the photographer is still faced with an ethical choice: whether to advance photography's truth-claims on the basis of these powers or to diminish or veil these powers to protect the integrity of the subject. Photography's acts of intrusion and destabilization, then, constantly test the photographer at the point of production, in the darkroom, and at the computer, especially in our 24-hour digital image culture. In this game-changing work, Roberts refunctions photography's place in the world, politically and theoretically restoring its reputation as a truth-producing medium.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aPhotographyxInfluence. 0aPhotographyxPhilosophy. 0aPhotographyxSocial aspects. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Aesthetics.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066586440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/robe1681840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231538244423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231538244.jpg  a978-3-11-066586-4  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles